sol:
The key insight in this problem is to first calculate the difference $a - b$ modulo 42. If the result is not within the desired range of 100 to 141, we can add multiples of 42 to the result until it falls within the range. This is possible because adding or subtracting the modulus (in this case, 42) to a number does not change its congruence class.
Step 1: Calculate $a - b \pmod{42}$.
$$\begin{align*}
a - b &\equiv 18 - 73 \pmod{42} \\
      &\equiv -55 \pmod{42} \\
      &\equiv -55 + 42 + 42 \pmod{42} \\
      &\equiv 29 \pmod{42}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Since $29 \not\in \{100, 101, \ldots, 141\}$, add multiples of 42 until the result is within the desired range.
$$\begin{align*}
29 &\equiv 29 + 42 \pmod{42} \\
   &\equiv 71 \pmod{42}
\end{align*}$$
$71 \not\in \{100, 101, \ldots, 141\}$, so we add 42 again:
$$\begin{align*}
71 &\equiv 71 + 42 \pmod{42} \\
   &\equiv 113 \pmod{42}
\end{align*}$$
Since $113 \in \{100, 101, \ldots, 141\}$, we have found the desired integer $n$.
The integer $n$ in the set $\{100, 101, 102, \ldots, 140, 141\}$ such that $a - b \equiv n \pmod{42}$ is $n = \boxed{113}$.
